Certain SMTP mail servers (in this case, mailjet.com) will throw an `AuthenticationException` when trying to send mail from an .NET Core console applications (or asp.net web applications) that are running on Linux.

For example:

    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            MainAsync().Wait();
        }

        public static async Task MainAsync()
        {
            try
            {
                var client = new SmtpClient("in-v3.mailjet.com", 587)
                {
                    EnableSsl = true,
                    DeliveryMethod = SmtpDeliveryMethod.Network,
                    Credentials = new NetworkCredential("user",
                        "password")
                };

                var message = new MailMessage
                {
                    From = new MailAddress("app@example.com"),
                    Subject = "Testing SMTP Email",
                    SubjectEncoding = Encoding.UTF8,
                    BodyEncoding = Encoding.UTF8,
                    BodyTransferEncoding = System.Net.Mime.TransferEncoding.QuotedPrintable,
                    Body = "<p>Hi, This is a test email.</p>",
                    IsBodyHtml = true
                };

                message.To.Add(new MailAddress("me@example.com"));
                client.SendCompleted += (sender, e) =>
                {
                    if(e.Error != null)
                    {
                        Console.WriteLine("SendCompleted Error: " + e.Error.Message + " : " + e.Error.ToString());
                    }

                    if(e.Cancelled)
                    {
                        Console.WriteLine("SendCompleted Cancelled");
                    }

                    message.Dispose();
                    client.Dispose();
                };

                client.SendAsync(message, null);
                Console.WriteLine("Mail sent.");
            }
            catch(Exception e)
            {
                Console.WriteLine("There was an exception. " + e.Message);
            }

            await Task.Delay(2000);
            Console.ReadLine();
            await Task.Delay(2000);
            Console.ReadLine();
        }
    }

Using my SMTP settings provided by mailjet.com (you can create a free account there to test), I can send email just fine from this application running locally (Windows 10) or when the application deployed to Azure as a Windows web app.

However, if I build this application into a Linux Docker image (asp.net or .net core runtime) or just run it on an Ubuntu desktop, it fails to send mail with an `AuthenticationException`.

> System.Net.Mail.SmtpException: Failure sending mail. ---> System.Security.Authentication.AuthenticationException: The remote certificate is invalid according to the validation procedure.

I can change my mail settings to another server, such as SendGrid, and it works fine both on my local Windows 10 machine, Azure, in the Docker container, and on the Ubuntu desktop.

It seems like this is a problem with a missing CA for mailjet's SSL cert or something, but I can see the DigiCert CA on all hosts and in the Linux docker container.

I don't understand why it works in other environments, but not a Docker container or on Ubuntu desktop.

When `Decoder.GetCharCount()` is called on two halves of a byte sequence, splitting a multi-byte character, it returns an incorrect count.

- The first call correctly ignores the partial character.
- The second half returns a count that is too great. Perhaps it is ignoring the unprocessed byte from the previous call.
- In contrast, `Decoder.GetChars()` seems to work correctly.
- Tested with UTF-8, splitting a 4-byte 💩 "pile of poo" after the first byte. _(How's that for getting your hands dirty!)_
- This bug seems to affect both .NET Core 2.1 and .NET Framework.

```
var str = "a💩a";
var bytes = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(str); // 'a', 4 bytes that make up the pile of poo, 'a'
var decoder = Encoding.UTF8.GetDecoder();

// Getting char count at once works as expected
var totalCharCount = decoder.GetCharCount(bytes, 0, bytes.Length); // 4
decoder.Reset();

// Getting chars at once works as expected
var chars1 = new char[4];
var expectedResult = decoder.GetChars(bytes, 0, bytes.Length, chars1, 0); // 4: chars 'a', 2 chars that make up the pile of poo, 'a'
decoder.Reset();

// Gettings chars in two goes works as expected
var chars2 = new char[4];
var chars2Position = decoder.GetChars(bytes, 0, 2, chars2, 0, flush: false); // Including 1 byte from pile of poo
decoder.GetChars(bytes, 2, bytes.Length - 2, chars2, chars2Position, flush: true); // The remaining bytes
var getCharsInTwoGoesIsCorrect = chars2.SequenceEqual(chars1); // True
decoder.Reset();

// Getting char count in two goes returns INCORRECT result
var leftCount = decoder.GetCharCount(bytes, 0, 2, flush: false); // 1, correctly ignoring the first byte of pile of poo
var rightCount = decoder.GetCharCount(bytes, 2, bytes.Length - 2, flush: true); // 4! incorrectly treating the additional 3 bytes of pile of poo as 3 characters
var getCharCountInTwoGoesIsCorrect = leftCount + rightCount == totalCharCount; // False!
```

